<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">List of Super Bowl champions</h1>
<div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content">
<div id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
<div id="contentSub"></div>
<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">
Jump to: <a href="#mw-head">navigation</a>, <a href="#p-search">search</a>
</div>
<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p>The <b><a href="/wiki/Super_Bowl" title="Super Bowl">Super Bowl</a></b> is an annual <a href="/wiki/American_football" title="American football">American football</a> game that determines the <b>champion of the <a href="/wiki/National_Football_League" title="National Football League">National Football League</a> (NFL)</b>. The contest is held in an American city, chosen three to four years beforehand,<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> usually at warm-weather sites or <a href="/wiki/Stadium#Types" title="Stadium">domed stadiums</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> Since January 1971, the winner of the <a href="/wiki/AFC_Championship_Game" title="AFC Championship Game">American Football Conference (AFC) Championship Game</a> has faced the winner of the <a href="/wiki/NFC_Championship_Game" title="NFC Championship Game">National Football Conference (NFC) Championship Game</a> in the culmination of the <a href="/wiki/National_Football_League_playoffs" title="National Football League playoffs">NFL playoffs</a>.</p>
<p>Before the <a href="/wiki/AFL%E2%80%93NFL_merger" title="AFL–NFL merger">1970 merger</a> between the <a href="/wiki/American_Football_League" title="American Football League">American Football League</a> (AFL) and the <a href="/wiki/National_Football_League" title="National Football League">National Football League</a> (NFL), the two leagues met in four such contests. The first two were known as the "AFL-NFL World Championship Game". <a href="/wiki/Super_Bowl_III" title="Super Bowl III">Super Bowl III</a> in 1969 was the first such game that carried the "Super Bowl" moniker, the names "<a href="/wiki/Super_Bowl_I" title="Super Bowl I">Super Bowl I</a>" and "<a href="/wiki/Super_Bowl_II" title="Super Bowl II">Super Bowl II</a>" were retroactively applied to the first two games.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/National_Football_Conference" title="National Football Conference">NFC</a>/NFL leads in Super Bowl wins with 26, while the <a href="/wiki/American_Football_Conference" title="American Football Conference">AFC</a>/AFL has won 24. Nineteen different franchises, including teams that relocated to another city, have won the Super Bowl.<sup id="cite_ref-record_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-record-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Pittsburgh_Steelers" title="Pittsburgh Steelers">Pittsburgh Steelers</a> (6–2) have won the most Super Bowls with six championships, while both the <a href="/wiki/San_Francisco_49ers" title="San Francisco 49ers">San Francisco 49ers</a> (5–1) and <a href="/wiki/Dallas_Cowboys" title="Dallas Cowboys">Dallas Cowboys</a> (5–3) have five wins. Dallas, Pittsburgh, <a href="/wiki/New_England_Patriots" title="New England Patriots">New England</a> and <a href="/wiki/Denver_Broncos" title="Denver Broncos">Denver</a> have the most Super Bowl appearances with eight, while the <a href="/wiki/Buffalo_Bills" title="Buffalo Bills">Buffalo Bills</a> (0–4) have the most consecutive appearances with four losses in a row from 1990 to 1993 (the <a href="/wiki/Miami_Dolphins" title="Miami Dolphins">Miami Dolphins</a> are the only other team to have at least three consecutive appearances: 1972–74). The <a href="/wiki/Denver_Broncos" title="Denver Broncos">Denver Broncos</a> (3–5) have lost a record five Super Bowls. The New England Patriots (4–4), the <a href="/wiki/Minnesota_Vikings" title="Minnesota Vikings">Minnesota Vikings</a> (0–4) and the Bills have lost four. The record for consecutive wins is two and is shared by seven franchises: the 1966–67 <a href="/wiki/Green_Bay_Packers" title="Green Bay Packers">Green Bay Packers</a>, the 1972–73 Miami Dolphins, the 1974–75 and 1978–79 Pittsburgh Steelers (the only team to accomplish this feat twice), the 1988–89 San Francisco 49ers, the 1992–93 Dallas Cowboys, the 1997–98 Denver Broncos, and the 2003–04 New England Patriots. Among those, Dallas (1992–93; 1995) and New England (2001; 2003-04) are the only teams to win three out of four consecutive Super Bowls. The <a href="/wiki/1972_Miami_Dolphins" title="1972 Miami Dolphins" class="mw-redirect">1972 Dolphins</a>' win is the only <a href="/wiki/Perfect_season" title="Perfect season">perfect season</a> in NFL history. The only team with multiple Super Bowl appearances and no losses is the <a href="/wiki/Baltimore_Ravens" title="Baltimore Ravens">Baltimore Ravens</a>, who in winning <a href="/wiki/Super_Bowl_XLVII" title="Super Bowl XLVII">Super Bowl XLVII</a> defeated and replaced the 49ers in that position. Four current NFL teams have never appeared in a Super Bowl, including franchise relocations and renaming: the <a href="/wiki/Cleveland_Browns" title="Cleveland Browns">Cleveland Browns</a>, <a href="/wiki/Detroit_Lions" title="Detroit Lions">Detroit Lions</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jacksonville_Jaguars" title="Jacksonville Jaguars">Jacksonville Jaguars</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Houston_Texans" title="Houston Texans">Houston Texans</a>, though both the Browns (1964) and Lions (1957) had won NFL championship games prior to the creation of the Super Bowl.</p>
<p></p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Super_Bowl_Championship_.281966.E2.80.93present.29">Super Bowl Championship (1966–present)</span></h2>
<p>Numbers in parentheses in the table are Super Bowl appearances, as of the date of that Super Bowl and are used as follows:</p>
<ul>
<li><b>Winning team</b> and <b>Losing team</b> columns indicate the number of times that team has appeared in a Super Bowl as well as each respective teams' Super Bowl record to date.</li>
<li><b>Venue</b> column indicates number of times that stadium has hosted a Super Bowl.</li>
<li><b>City</b> column indicates number of times that that metropolitan area has hosted a Super Bowl.</li>
</ul>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Consecutive_repeat_winners">Consecutive repeat winners</span></h3>
<p>Seven different franchises have won consecutive Super Bowls, one of which has accomplished it twice:</p>
<ul>
<li>Green Bay Packers (Super Bowls I and II)</li>
<li>Miami Dolphins (VII and VIII)</li>
<li>Pittsburgh Steelers (twice: IX and X as well as XIII and XIV)</li>
<li>San Francisco 49ers (XXIII and XXIV)</li>
<li>Dallas Cowboys (XXVII and XXVIII)</li>
<li>Denver Broncos (XXXII and XXXIII)</li>
<li>New England Patriots (XXXVIII and XXXIX)</li>
</ul>
<p>No franchise has yet won three Super Bowls in a row, although several have come close:</p>
<ul>
<li>The Green Bay Packers won the first two Super Bowls, and also won the NFL championship the preceding year.</li>
<li>The Miami Dolphins appeared in three consecutive Super Bowls (VI, VII, and VIII), winning the last two.</li>
<li>The Pittsburgh Steelers won two consecutive Super Bowls (IX and X); the following season they were eliminated in the AFC championship game by the eventual Super Bowl champion Oakland Raiders.</li>
<li>The San Francisco 49ers won two consecutive Super Bowls (XXIII and XXIV); the following season they were eliminated in the NFC championship by the eventual Super Bowl champion New York Giants.</li>
<li>The Dallas Cowboys won two consecutive Super Bowls (XXVII and XXVIII); the following season they were eliminated in the NFC championship game by the eventual champion San Francisco 49ers. The Cowboys won Super Bowl XXX the following year for three wins in four seasons.</li>
</ul>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Teams_with_no_Super_Bowl_appearances">Teams with no Super Bowl appearances</span></h3>
<p>Four current teams have never reached the Super Bowl. Two of them held <a href="/wiki/List_of_NFL_champions_(1920%E2%80%9369)" title="List of NFL champions (1920–69)">NFL league championships</a> prior to <a href="/wiki/Super_Bowl_I" title="Super Bowl I">Super Bowl I</a> in the <a href="/wiki/1966_NFL_season" title="1966 NFL season">1966 NFL season</a>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Detroit Lions, NFL champions four times in <a href="/wiki/1935_NFL_season" title="1935 NFL season">1935</a>, <a href="/wiki/1952_NFL_season" title="1952 NFL season">1952</a>, <a href="/wiki/1953_NFL_season" title="1953 NFL season">1953</a>, and <a href="/wiki/1957_NFL_season" title="1957 NFL season">1957</a>; appeared in one other <a href="/wiki/List_of_NFL_champions_(1920%E2%80%931969)" title="List of NFL champions (1920–1969)" class="mw-redirect">NFL Championship Game</a> in <a href="/wiki/1954_NFL_Championship_Game" title="1954 NFL Championship Game">1954</a>; and appeared in one <a href="/wiki/NFC_Championship_Game" title="NFC Championship Game">NFC Championship Game</a> in <a href="/wiki/NFL_playoffs,_1991-92#NFC:_Washington_Redskins_41.2C_Detroit_Lions_10" title="NFL playoffs, 1991-92" class="mw-redirect">1991</a><sup id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-75"><span>[</span>70<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Cleveland Browns, NFL champions four times in <a href="/wiki/1950_NFL_season" title="1950 NFL season">1950</a>, <a href="/wiki/1954_NFL_season" title="1954 NFL season">1954</a>, <a href="/wiki/1955_NFL_season" title="1955 NFL season">1955</a>, and <a href="/wiki/1964_NFL_season" title="1964 NFL season">1964</a>; appeared in six other NFL championship games in <a href="/wiki/1951_NFL_Championship_Game" title="1951 NFL Championship Game">1951</a>, <a href="/wiki/1952_NFL_Championship_Game" title="1952 NFL Championship Game">1952</a>, <a href="/wiki/1953_NFL_Championship_Game" title="1953 NFL Championship Game">1953</a>, <a href="/wiki/1957_NFL_Championship_Game" title="1957 NFL Championship Game">1957</a>, <a href="/wiki/1968_NFL_Championship_Game" title="1968 NFL Championship Game">1968</a>, and <a href="/wiki/1969_NFL_Championship_Game" title="1969 NFL Championship Game">1969</a>; and appeared in three <a href="/wiki/AFC_Championship_Game" title="AFC Championship Game">AFC Championship Games</a> in <a href="/wiki/NFL_playoffs,_1986-87#AFC:_Denver_Broncos_23.2C_Cleveland_Browns_20_.28OT.29" title="NFL playoffs, 1986-87" class="mw-redirect">1986</a>, <a href="/wiki/NFL_playoffs,_1987-88#AFC:_Denver_Broncos_38.2C_Cleveland_Browns_33" title="NFL playoffs, 1987-88" class="mw-redirect">1987</a>, and <a href="/wiki/NFL_playoffs,_1989-90#AFC:_Denver_Broncos_37.2C_Cleveland_Browns_21" title="NFL playoffs, 1989-90" class="mw-redirect">1989</a><sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76"><span>[</span>71<span>]</span></a></sup> <small>(The Browns are officially viewed as one continuous franchise that began in 1946 as a member of the <a href="/wiki/All-America_Football_Conference" title="All-America Football Conference">All-America Football Conference</a>, joined the NFL in <a href="/wiki/1950_NFL_season" title="1950 NFL season">1950</a>, suspended operations from <a href="/wiki/1996_NFL_season" title="1996 NFL season">1996</a>–<a href="/wiki/1998_NFL_season" title="1998 NFL season">1998</a>, and resumed play in <a href="/wiki/1999_NFL_season" title="1999 NFL season">1999</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-77"><span>[</span>72<span>]</span></a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Baltimore_Ravens" title="Baltimore Ravens">Baltimore Ravens</a> were an <a href="/wiki/Expansion_team" title="Expansion team">expansion team</a> created in <a href="/wiki/1996_NFL_season" title="1996 NFL season">1996</a> with former Browns players.)<sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78"><span>[</span>73<span>]</span></a></sup></small></li>
<li>Jacksonville Jaguars, <a href="/wiki/1995_NFL_season" title="1995 NFL season">1995</a> expansion team; appeared in two AFC Championship Games in <a href="/wiki/NFL_playoffs,_1996-97#AFC:_New_England_Patriots_20.2C_Jacksonville_Jaguars_6" title="NFL playoffs, 1996-97" class="mw-redirect">1996</a> and <a href="/wiki/NFL_playoffs,_1999-00#AFC:_Tennessee_Titans_33.2C_Jacksonville_Jaguars_14" title="NFL playoffs, 1999-00" class="mw-redirect">1999</a><sup id="cite_ref-79" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-79"><span>[</span>74<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Houston Texans, <a href="/wiki/2002_NFL_season" title="2002 NFL season">2002</a> expansion team; two Divisional Round appearances in 2011 and 2012.</li>
</ul>
<p>In addition, Detroit, Houston and Jacksonville have hosted Super Bowls; this means Cleveland is the only current NFL city that has neither hosted, nor had their team play in, a Super Bowl.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Teams_with_Super_Bowl_appearances_but_no_victories">Teams with Super Bowl appearances but no victories</span></h3>
<p>Nine teams have appeared in the Super Bowl without ever winning. In descending order of number of appearances, they are:</p>
<ul>
<li>Buffalo Bills (4), appeared in Super Bowls XXV, XXVI, XXVII, and XXVIII. Their second and last AFL championship was in <a href="/wiki/1965_AFL_season" title="1965 AFL season" class="mw-redirect">1965</a>, the season before the <a href="/wiki/Super_Bowl_I" title="Super Bowl I">first</a> Super Bowl.</li>
<li>Minnesota Vikings (4), appeared in Super Bowls IV, VIII, IX, and XI. They were NFL champions in <a href="/wiki/1969_NFL_season" title="1969 NFL season">1969</a>, the last year before the AFL–NFL merger.</li>
<li>Cincinnati Bengals (2), appeared in Super Bowls XVI and XXIII. An AFL expansion team in <a href="/wiki/1968_Cincinnati_Bengals_season" title="1968 Cincinnati Bengals season">1968</a>, they have no pre-Super Bowl league championships.</li>
<li>Philadelphia Eagles (2), appeared in Super Bowls XV and XXXIX. Their last championship was in <a href="/wiki/1960_NFL_season" title="1960 NFL season">1960</a>.</li>
<li>Carolina Panthers (2), appeared in Super Bowls XXXVIII and 50. A post-merger expansion team, their first season was in <a href="/wiki/1995_Carolina_Panthers_season" title="1995 Carolina Panthers season">1995</a>.</li>
<li>Arizona Cardinals (1), appeared in Super Bowl XLIII. Their last championship was in <a href="/wiki/1947_NFL_season" title="1947 NFL season">1947</a> as the <a href="/wiki/History_of_the_Chicago_Cardinals" title="History of the Chicago Cardinals">Chicago Cardinals</a>.</li>
<li>Atlanta Falcons (1), appeared in Super Bowl XXXIII. An expansion team in <a href="/wiki/1966_Atlanta_Falcons_season" title="1966 Atlanta Falcons season">1966</a>, they have no pre-Super Bowl league championships.</li>
<li>San Diego Chargers (1), appeared in Super Bowl XXIX. Their only AFL championship was in <a href="/wiki/1963_AFL_season" title="1963 AFL season" class="mw-redirect">1963</a>.</li>
<li>Tennessee Titans (1), appeared in Super Bowl XXXIV. Their second and last AFL championship was in <a href="/wiki/1961_AFL_season" title="1961 AFL season" class="mw-redirect">1961</a> as the <a href="/wiki/History_of_the_Houston_Oilers" title="History of the Houston Oilers">Houston Oilers</a>.</li>
</ul>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Teams_with_long_Super_Bowl_droughts">Teams with long Super Bowl droughts</span></h3>
<p>The following eight teams have appeared in the Super Bowl, but not since 1995, meaning their droughts are longer than Jacksonville's and Houston's.</p>
<p>Two of these teams have not appeared in the Super Bowl since the <a href="/wiki/AFL%E2%80%93NFL_merger" title="AFL–NFL merger">AFL–NFL merger</a> in 1970:<sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-80"><span>[</span>75<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<ul>
<li>New York Jets (most recently appeared in Super Bowl III, <a href="/wiki/1968_NFL_season" title="1968 NFL season">1968 season</a>)</li>
<li>Kansas City Chiefs (Super Bowl IV in <a href="/wiki/1969_NFL_season" title="1969 NFL season">1969 season</a>)</li>
</ul>
<p>The most recent Super Bowl appearance for the following teams was after the AFL–NFL merger, but prior to the 1995 regular season:</p>
<ul>
<li>Minnesota Vikings (Super Bowl XI, <a href="/wiki/1976_NFL_season" title="1976 NFL season">1976 season</a>)</li>
<li>Miami Dolphins (Super Bowl XIX, <a href="/wiki/1984_NFL_season" title="1984 NFL season">1984 season</a>)</li>
<li>Cincinnati Bengals (Super Bowl XXIII, <a href="/wiki/1988_NFL_season" title="1988 NFL season">1988 season</a>)</li>
<li>Washington Redskins (Super Bowl XXVI, <a href="/wiki/1991_NFL_season" title="1991 NFL season">1991 season</a>)</li>
<li>Buffalo Bills (Super Bowl XXVIII, <a href="/wiki/1993_NFL_season" title="1993 NFL season">1993 season</a>)</li>
<li>San Diego Chargers (Super Bowl XXIX, <a href="/wiki/1994_NFL_season" title="1994 NFL season">1994 season</a>)</li>
</ul>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Super_Bowl_rematches">Super Bowl rematches</span></h3>
<p>The following teams have faced each other more than once in the Super Bowl:</p>
<ul>
<li>Dallas Cowboys and Pittsburgh Steelers (3) – Super Bowls X and XIII were won by Pittsburgh, and Super Bowl XXX was won by <a href="/wiki/1995_Dallas_Cowboys_season" title="1995 Dallas Cowboys season">Dallas</a>. <i>See also</i> <a href="/wiki/Cowboys%E2%80%93Steelers_rivalry" title="Cowboys–Steelers rivalry">Cowboys–Steelers rivalry</a>.</li>
<li>Miami Dolphins and Washington Redskins (2) – Super Bowl VII was won by <a href="/wiki/1972_Miami_Dolphins_season" title="1972 Miami Dolphins season">Miami</a>, and Super Bowl XVII was won by <a href="/wiki/1982_Washington_Redskins_season" title="1982 Washington Redskins season">Washington</a>.</li>
<li>Cincinnati Bengals and San Francisco 49ers (2) – Super Bowls XVI and XXIII were both won by San Francisco.</li>
<li>Buffalo Bills and Dallas Cowboys (2) – Super Bowls XXVII and XXVIII were both won by Dallas, in consecutive seasons.</li>
<li>New England Patriots and New York Giants (2) – Super Bowls XLII and XLVI were both won by New York.</li>
</ul>

title="Detroit, Michigan" class="mw-redirect">Detroit</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6"><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup> Both <a href="/wiki/Tempe,_Arizona" Arizona</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a <li id="cite_note-b-13"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-b_13-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-b_13-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-b_13-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-b_13-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-b_13-4"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-b_13-5"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-b_13-6"><sup><i><b>g</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-b_13-7"><sup><i><b>h</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-b_13-8"><sup><i><b>i</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-b_13-9"><sup><i><b>j</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/Miami_Gardens,_Florida" title="Miami Gardens, Florida">Miami Gardens</a> was incorporated as a <a href="/wiki/Suburb" title="Suburb">suburb</a> of <a href="/wiki/Miami,_Florida" title="Miami, Florida" class="mw-redirect">Miami</a> in 2003. Prior to that, it had been an <a href="/wiki/Unincorporated_area" title="Unincorporated area">unincorporated area</a> of <a href="/wiki/Miami-Dade_County,_Florida" title="Miami-Dade County, Florida">Miami-Dade County</a> but the stadium had a Miami address.<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12"><span>[</span>11<span>]</span></a></sup></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-d-38"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-d_38-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-d_38-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-d_38-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-d_38-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-d_38-4"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-d_38-5"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-d_38-6"><sup><i><b>g</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-d_38-7"><sup><i><b>h</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-d_38-8"><sup><i><b>i</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-d_38-9"><sup><i><b>j</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/Qualcomm_Stadium" title="Qualcomm Stadium">Qualcomm Stadium</a> was originally known as San Diego Stadium and Jack Murphy Stadium.<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34"><span>[</span>32<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Dolphin_Stadium" title="Dolphin Stadium" class="mw-redirect">Dolphin Stadium</a> has also been variously known over the years as Joe Robbie Stadium, Pro Player Park, Pro Player Stadium, Land Shark Stadium, and Dolphins Stadium (with a plural "s"). Its subsequent name of Dolphin Stadium (with no "s") was also the original name it was given when first built. It is currently known as <a href="/wiki/Sun_Life_Stadium" title="Sun Life Stadium">Sun Life Stadium</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-buffet_35-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-buffet-35"><span>[</span>33<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36"><span>[</span>34<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/NRG_Stadium" title="NRG Stadium">NRG Stadium</a> was originally known as Reliant Stadium.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37"><span>[</span>35<span>]</span></a></sup></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-future-71"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-future_71-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-future_71-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Dates are tentative, pending possible future changes to the NFL calendar.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-e-74"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-e_74-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-e_74-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-e_74-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-e_74-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">The Colts moved over to the newly formed AFC in 1970. Additionally, two other teams also made the move from the old NFL, the Steelers and Browns.</span></li>
